The national report of the task
force on Man Power Conserva-
ton made it's final report to
President Lyndon B. Johnson. 1t
was entitled, "One-Third OF
Nation" which gave findings on
Young men who were unqualified
for military service.


The report concluded that one
third of all the young men in our
country turning l0 would be found
unqualified If they were examined
for the armed forces. One Of
every two selective service re-
gistrants called for pre-induc-
ton examinations Is now undual-
flied. The majority Of the re-
iectees were caused by made
ouate education and to a lesser
degree insufficient medical care.
These same young men face a
lifetime of recurrent unemploy-
ment.


Rates of mental tests failures
for whites and Negroes showed
wide variations. Nationally, So
per cent of the Negroes who had
pre-inductions examinations in
1862 failed the tests, as COM
pared to Is per cent of the white.


Negro rejection rates in some
kof the western states. were less
than one-half of the national av-
erage for Negroes, and we're only
slightly above the rejection rates
for white registrants in certain
northeastern states.


Four out Of five rejectees were
school dropouts, nearly one half
had left school before II. FL
nancial reasons were greater
among nonwhites than whites.


Three out of 10 rejectees
we're unemployed. More than four
of every five rejectees wanted
job training.

WASHINGTON-Swedish econo-
mist Gunnar Myrdal advises the
American people to cut taxes and
expand government spending.


DR.. Myrdal, whose research
study on American Negroes, IAN
American Dilemma" served as
a focal point Of many further
studies in the early 40 8, said
the II billion dollar tax cut would
help the nation fight poverty.
The noted writer said Negroes
should have equality $50 far as
the law is concerned" and pre-
dicted they will have 1t within
ten years.


He added that preferential hir-
ing Of Negroes would be wrong.
Myrdal said, Negroes are not
alone, there are porr whites
all over the place."

LTIMORE = Hank Aaron,
smuggling ballplayer of the Mil
waukee Braves, was presented
with a Sultan of Swat crown for
1868. He tied with Willie Nc
Covey of San Francisco for home
run honors in the major leagues
last season. Each hit "A.


Hank received 5000 cash
award with the crown. He was un-
able to attend the 18th annual Tops
in Sports banquet because Of the
heavy snowstorms.


Joe DiMaggio, a former Yankee
star, also received a crown for
his hitting deeds In 1899.


Others who have won the awards
include Mickey Mantle, Ted Will
liams, Ernie Banks, Eddie Math-
ews, Roger Maris. and Willie
Mays.

NEW YORK The general fund
income of the National Associa-
ton for the Advancement Of
Colored People was $l,5l3-
$500 in 1868. a 27.3 per cent
increase over ST. .06o, l04.3O re-
ceived by the Associations ma
tional general fund in 1862.


This report of NAACP trea-
surer, Alfred Baker Lewis, was
given at the annual NAACP meet
ing here. Jan. 6.


In addition, life membership
committee, reached an all-time
high Of $334,883.00. Another
$88, $3.50 was received in requests.


Operating expenses exclusive
of bail bond money! amounted to
$1.576,146.00, leaving a deficit
of $62,493.Oo, a sharp reduc-
ton from the 1862 deficit of
$244,387.73. AS in former years.
the deficit will be met by trans
fer of money from the life mem
bership fund over and above the
annual appointments from this
source.

A MILLION AND HALF

NEW YORK = Negro lawyer Leon
Higginbotham, Jr. has been
named one of "America's Ten
Outstanding Young Men, by the
United States Junior Chamber Of
Commerce.


The selections we're announced
this week in Look Magazine.


Higginbotham, who won this
honor out of a field Of 200
top candidates, "was "a when
President Kennedy nominated
him for the Federal Trade Com
mission" Look said. "He be-
came the youngest man ever ap-
pointed to that body and the first
Negro commissioner Of a Federal
regulatory agency"


Higginbotham believes: enc
groes have an obligation to foster
maximum motivations among
young people to develop their
potential"

from his native country.
